TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Derivation of the Underlying Constructs of Just-In-Time Management Systems
AU  - Davy, Jeanette A.
AU  - White, Richard E.
AU  - Merritt, Nancy J.
AU  - Gritzmacher, Karen
Y1  - 1992/08/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256491
DO  - 10.5465/256491
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 653
EP  - 670
VL  - 35
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Researchers have recommended that the theoretical constructs underlying just-in-time (JIT) management systems be identified and developed if JIT is to be fully understood and its full capabilities realized. In this study, we advanced this conceptual development through an instrument based on the relevant literature and empirically deriving three underlying constructs: (1) operating structure and control, (2) product scheduling, and (3) quality implementation. We report a content analysis of these constructs and develop propositions regarding their relationships, predecessors, and outcomes.
AB  - Researchers have recommended that the theoretical constructs underlying just-in-time (JIT) management systems be identified and developed if JIT is to be fully understood and its full capabilities realized. In this study, we advanced this conceptual development through an instrument based on the relevant literature and empirically deriving three underlying constructs: (1) operating structure and control, (2) product scheduling, and (3) quality implementation. We report a content analysis of these constructs and develop propositions regarding their relationships, predecessors, and outcomes.
